# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: structural-health-monitoring
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] In particular, AE occurs during the processes of *mechanical loading* of materials and structures accompanied by structural changes that generate local sources of elastic waves.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] This results in small surface displacements of a material produced by elastic or stress waves generated when the accumulated elastic energy in a material or on its surface is released rapidly.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] The mechanism of emission of the primary elastic pulse AE (act or event AE) may have a different physical nature.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] The AE method makes it possible to study the kinetics of processes at the earliest stages of microdeformation, dislocation nucleation and accumulation of microcracks.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Roughly speaking, each crack seems to "scream" about its growth.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] This makes it possible to diagnose the moment of crack origin itself by the accompanying AE.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] In addition, for each crack that has already arisen, there is a certain critical size, depending on the properties of the material.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Up to this size, the crack grows very slowly (sometimes for decades) through a huge number of small discrete jumps accompanied by AE radiation.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] After the crack reaches a critical size, catastrophic destruction occurs, because its further growth is already at a speed close to half the speed of sound in the material of the structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] The waves generated by sources of AE are of practical interest in structural health monitoring (SHM), quality control, system feedback, process monitoring, and other fields.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] In SHM applications, AE is typically used to detect, locate, and characterise damage.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Acoustic emission is associated with transient elastic waves within a material, caused by the rapid release of localized stress energy.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] An *event* source is defined by the release of the elastic energy into the material, which then propagates as elastic waves.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Acoustic emissions can be detected in frequency ranges under 1 kHz, and have been reported at frequencies up to 100 MHz, but most of the released energy is within the 1 kHz to 1 MHz range.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Rapid stress-releasing events generate a spectrum of stress waves starting at 0 Hz, and typically falling off at several MHz.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] More recent research has focused on using AE to not only locate but also to characterise the source mechanisms such as crack growth, friction, delamination, matrix cracking, etc.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] This would give AE the ability to tell the end user what source mechanism is present and allow them to determine whether structural repairs are necessary.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Employing proper signal processing and analysis allows for the possibility to gain a deeper understanding of the elastic wave signals and their relation to processes occurring within structures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] The frequency domain representation of a signal obtained through Fast Fourier transform (FFT) provides information about the signal's magnitude and frequency content.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] AE can be related to an irreversible release of energy.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] It can also be generated from sources not involving material failure, including friction, cavitation, and impact.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] The application of acoustic emission to nondestructive testing of materials typically takes place between 20 kHz and 1 MHz.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Unlike conventional ultrasonic testing, AE tools are designed for monitoring acoustic emissions produced by the material during failure or stress, and not on the material's effect on externally generated waves.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Part failure can be documented during unattended monitoring.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] The monitoring of the level of AE activity during multiple load cycles forms the basis for many AE safety inspection methods, that allow the parts undergoing inspection to remain in service.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] The technique is used, for example, to study the formation of cracks during the welding process, as opposed to locating them after the weld has been formed with the more familiar ultrasonic testing technique.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] In materials under active stress, such as some components of an airplane during flight, transducers mounted in an area can detect the formation of a crack at the moment it begins propagating.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] A group of transducers can be used to record signals and then locate the precise area of their origin by measuring the time for the sound to reach different transducers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Long-term continuous monitoring for acoustic emissions is valuable for detecting cracks forming in pressure vessels and pipelines transporting liquids under high pressures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Standards for the use of acoustic emission for nondestructive testing of pressure vessels have been developed by the ASME, ISO, and the European Community.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] This technique is used for estimation of corrosion in reinforced concrete structures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] AE sensing can potentially be utilised to monitor the state of health of lithium-ion batteries, particularly in the detection and characterisation of parasitic mechano-electrochemical events, such as electrode electrochemical grinding, phase transitions, and gas evolution.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] The piezoelectric sensor is employed to receive acoustic signals released by battery materials during operation.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] In addition to nondestructive testing, acoustic emission monitoring has applications in process monitoring.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/acoustic-emission] Applications where acoustic emission monitoring has successfully been used include detecting anomalies in fluidized beds and end points in batch granulation.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In materials science, **fatigue** is the initiation and propagation of cracks in a material due to cyclic loading.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Once a fatigue crack has initiated, it grows a small amount with each loading cycle, typically producing striations on some parts of the fracture surface.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The crack will continue to grow until it reaches a critical size, which occurs when the stress intensity factor of the crack exceeds the fracture toughness of the material, producing rapid propagation and typically complete fracture of the structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Fatigue has traditionally been associated with the failure of metal components which led to the term **metal fatigue**.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In the nineteenth century, the sudden failing of metal railway axles was thought to be caused by the metal crystallising because of the brittle appearance of the fracture surface, but this has since been disproved.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Most materials, such as composites, plastics and ceramics, seem to experience some sort of fatigue-related failure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] To aid in predicting the fatigue life of a component, fatigue tests are carried out using coupons to measure the rate of crack growth by applying constant amplitude cyclic loading and averaging the measured growth of a crack over thousands of cycles.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] If the loads are above a certain threshold, microscopic cracks will begin to initiate at stress concentrations such as holes, persistent slip bands (PSBs), composite interfaces or grain boundaries in metals.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The stress values that cause fatigue damage are typically much less than the yield strength of the material.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Historically, fatigue has been separated into regions of high cycle fatigue that require more than 104 cycles to failure where stress is low and primarily elastic and low cycle fatigue where there is significant plasticity.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Experiments have shown that low cycle fatigue is also crack growth.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Fatigue failures, both for high and low cycles, all follow the same basic steps: crack initiation, crack growth stages I and II, and finally ultimate failure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] To begin the process, cracks must nucleate within a material.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This process can occur either at stress risers in metallic samples or at areas with a high void density in polymer samples.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] These cracks propagate slowly at first during stage I crack growth along crystallographic planes, where shear stresses are highest.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Once the cracks reach a critical size they propagate quickly during stage II crack growth in a direction perpendicular to the applied force.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] These cracks can eventually lead to the ultimate failure of the material, often in a brittle catastrophic fashion.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The formation of initial cracks preceding fatigue failure is a separate process consisting of four discrete steps in metallic samples.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The material will develop cell structures and harden in response to the applied load.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This causes the amplitude of the applied stress to increase given the new restraints on strain.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] These newly formed cell structures will eventually break down with the formation of persistent slip bands (PSBs).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Slip in the material is localized at these PSBs, and the exaggerated slip can now serve as a stress concentrator for a crack to form.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Nucleation and growth of a crack to a detectable size accounts for most of the cracking process.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] It is for this reason that cyclic fatigue failures seem to occur so suddenly where the bulk of the changes in the material are not visible without destructive testing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Even in normally ductile materials, fatigue failures will resemble sudden brittle failures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] PSB-induced slip planes result in intrusions and extrusions along the surface of a material, often occurring in pairs.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This slip is not a microstructural change within the material, but rather a propagation of dislocations within the material.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Instead of a smooth interface, the intrusions and extrusions will cause the surface of the material to resemble the edge of a deck of cards, where not all cards are perfectly aligned.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Slip-induced intrusions and extrusions create extremely fine surface structures on the material.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] With surface structure size inversely related to stress concentration factors, PSB-induced surface slip can cause fractures to initiate.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] These steps can also be bypassed entirely if the cracks form at a pre-existing stress concentrator such as from an inclusion in the material or from a geometric stress concentrator caused by a sharp internal corner or fillet.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Most of the fatigue life is generally consumed in the crack growth phase.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The rate of growth is primarily driven by the range of cyclic loading although additional factors such as mean stress, environment, overloads and underloads can also affect the rate of growth.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Crack growth may stop if the loads are small enough to fall below a critical threshold.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Fatigue cracks can grow from material or manufacturing defects from as small as 10 μm.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] When the rate of growth becomes large enough, fatigue striations can be seen on the fracture surface.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Striations mark the position of the crack tip and the width of each striation represents the growth from one loading cycle.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Striations are a result of plasticity at the crack tip.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] When the stress intensity exceeds a critical value known as the fracture toughness, unsustainable fast fracture will occur, usually by a process of microvoid coalescence.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Prior to final fracture, the fracture surface may contain a mixture of areas of fatigue and fast fracture.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The American Society for Testing and Materials defines fatigue life, Nf, as the number of stress cycles of a specified character that a specimen sustains before failure of a specified nature occurs.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] For some materials, like steel and titanium, there is a theoretical value for stress amplitude below which the material will not fail for any number of cycles, called a fatigue limit or endurance limit.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In practice, several bodies of work done at greater numbers of cycles suggest that fatigue limits do not exist for any metals.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] 4. probabilistic methods, which can be based on either life or crack growth methods.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Whether using stress/strain-life approach or using crack growth approach, complex or variable amplitude loading is reduced to a series of fatigue equivalent simple cyclic loadings using a technique such as the rainflow-counting algorithm.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] A mechanical part is often exposed to a complex, often random, sequence of loads, large and small.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The effect of the individual contributions are combined using an algorithm such as Miner's rule.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Since S-N curves are typically generated for uniaxial loading, some equivalence rule is needed whenever the loading is multiaxial.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] For simple, proportional loading histories (lateral load in a constant ratio with the axial), Sines rule may be applied.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] For more complex situations, such as non-proportional loading, critical plane analysis must be applied.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Miner popularised a rule that had first been proposed by Arvid Palmgren in 1924.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Usually, for design purposes, C is assumed to be 1.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This can be thought of as assessing what proportion of life is consumed by a linear combination of stress reversals at varying magnitudes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The sequence in which high vs. low stress cycles are applied to a sample in fact affect the fatigue life, for which Miner's Rule does not account.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In some circumstances, cycles of low stress followed by high stress cause more damage than would be predicted by the rule.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] It does not consider the effect of an overload or high stress which may result in a compressive residual stress that may retard crack growth.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] High stress followed by low stress may have less damage due to the presence of compressive residual stress (or localized plastic damages around crack tip).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Materials fatigue performance is commonly characterized by an *S-N curve*, also known as a Wöhler curve.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This is often plotted with the cyclic stress (*S*) against the cycles to failure (*N*) on a logarithmic scale.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] S-N curves are derived from tests on samples of the material to be characterized (often called coupons or specimens) where a regular sinusoidal stress is applied by a testing machine which also counts the number of cycles to failure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This process is sometimes known as coupon testing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] For greater accuracy but lower generality component testing is used.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Each coupon or component test generates a point on the plot though in some cases there is a runout where the time to failure exceeds that available for the test (see censoring).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Analysis of fatigue data requires techniques from statistics, especially survival analysis, linear regression and extreme value analysis.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The progression of the *S-N curve* can be influenced by many factors such as stress ratio (mean stress), loading frequency, temperature, corrosion, residual stresses, and the presence of notches.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] A constant fatigue life (CFL) diagram is useful for the study of stress ratio effect.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The Goodman line is a method used to estimate the influence of the mean stress on the fatigue strength.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] A Constant Fatigue Life (CFL) diagram is useful for stress ratio effect on S-N curve.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Also, in the presence of a steady stress superimposed on the cyclic loading, the Goodman relation can be used to estimate a failure condition.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] It plots stress amplitude against mean stress with the fatigue limit and the ultimate tensile strength of the material as the two extremes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Alternative failure criteria include Soderberg and Gerber.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] As coupons sampled from a homogeneous frame will display a variation in their number of cycles to failure, the S-N curve should more properly be a Stress-Cycle-Probability (S-N-P) curve to capture the probability of failure after a given number of cycles of a certain stress.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] With body-centered cubic materials (bcc), the Wöhler curve often becomes a horizontal line with decreasing stress amplitude, i.e. there is a fatigue strength that can be assigned to these materials.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] With face-centered cubic metals (fcc), the Wöhler curve generally drops continuously, so that only a fatigue limit can be assigned to these materials.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] When strains are no longer elastic, such as in the presence of stress concentrations, the total strain can be used instead of stress as a similitude parameter.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This is known as the strain-life method.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] where $\sigma _{\text{f}}^{\prime }$ is a parameter that scales with tensile strength obtained by fitting experimental data, $N_{\text{f}}$ is the number of cycles to failure and b is the slope of the log-log curve again determined by curve fitting.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] where $\sigma _{f}'$ is the fatigue strength coefficient, b is the fatigue strength exponent, $\varepsilon _{f}'$ is the fatigue ductility coefficient, c is the fatigue ductility exponent, and $N_{f}$ is the number of cycles to failure ( $2N_{f}$ being the number of reversals to failure).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] An estimate of the fatigue life of a component can be made using a crack growth equation by summing up the width of each increment of crack growth for each loading cycle.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Safety or scatter factors are applied to the calculated life to account for any uncertainty and variability associated with fatigue.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The rate of growth used in crack growth predictions is typically measured by applying thousands of constant amplitude cycles to a coupon and measuring the rate of growth from the change in compliance of the coupon or by measuring the growth of the crack on the surface of the coupon.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Standard methods for measuring the rate of growth have been developed by ASTM International.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Crack growth equations such as the Paris–Erdoğan equation are used to predict the life of a component.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] They can be used to predict the growth of a crack from 10 um to failure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] For normal manufacturing finishes this may cover most of the fatigue life of a component where growth can start from the first cycle.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The conditions at the crack tip of a component are usually related to the conditions of test coupon using a characterising parameter such as the stress intensity, J-integral or crack tip opening displacement.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] All these techniques aim to match the crack tip conditions on the component to that of test coupons which give the rate of crack growth.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Additional models may be necessary to include retardation and acceleration effects associated with overloads or underloads in the loading sequence.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In addition, small crack growth data may be needed to match the increased rate of growth seen with small cracks.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Typically, a cycle counting technique such as rainflow-cycle counting is used to extract the cycles from a complex sequence.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This technique, along with others, has been shown to work with crack growth methods.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Crack growth methods have the advantage that they can predict the intermediate size of cracks.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This information can be used to schedule inspections on a structure to ensure safety whereas strain/life methods only give a life until failure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Dependable design against fatigue-failure requires thorough education and supervised experience in structural engineering, mechanical engineering, or materials science.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Fail-safe, graceful degradation, and fault-tolerant design: Instruct the user to replace parts when they fail.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Design in such a way that there is no single point of failure, and so that when any one part completely fails, it does not lead to catastrophic failure of the entire system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Damage tolerance: Is an approach that ensures aircraft safety by assuming the presence of cracks or defects even in new aircraft.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Crack growth calculations, periodic inspections and component repair or replacement can be used to ensure critical components that may contain cracks, remain safe.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Inspections usually use nondestructive testing to limit or monitor the size of possible cracks and require an accurate prediction of the rate of crack-growth between inspections.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The designer sets some aircraft maintenance checks schedule frequent enough that parts are replaced while the crack is still in the "slow growth" phase.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This is often referred to as damage tolerant design or "retirement-for-cause".
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Risk Management: Ensures the probability of failure remains below an acceptable level.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This approach is typically used for aircraft where acceptable levels may be based on probability of failure during a single flight or taken over the lifetime of an aircraft.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] A component is assumed to have a crack with a probability distribution of crack sizes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This approach can consider variability in values such as crack growth rates, usage and critical crack size.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] It is also useful for considering damage at multiple locations that may interact to produce multi-site or widespread fatigue damage.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Probability distributions that are common in data analysis and in design against fatigue include the log-normal distribution, extreme value distribution, Birnbaum–Saunders distribution, and Weibull distribution.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] 4. the origin and cause of the crack initiating defect from fractographic examination of the crack.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] These tests may form part of the certification process such as for airworthiness certification.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Small cracks can be blended away and the surface cold worked or shot peened.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Holes with cracks growing from them can be drilled out to a larger hole to remove cracking and bushed to restore the original hole.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Bushes can be cold shrink interference fit bushes to induce beneficial compressive residual stresses.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The oversized hole can also be cold worked by drawing an oversized mandrel through the hole.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Cracks may be repaired by installing a patch or repair fitting.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Composite patches have been used to restore the strength of aircraft wings after cracks have been detected or to lower the stress prior to cracking in order to improve the fatigue life.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Patches may restrict the ability to monitor fatigue cracks and may need to be removed and replaced for inspections.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Peening a surface can reduce such tensile stresses and create compressive residual stress, which prevents crack initiation.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Forms of peening include: shot peening, using high-speed projectiles, high-frequency impact treatment (also called high-frequency mechanical impact) using a mechanical hammer, and laser peening which uses high-energy laser pulses.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Low plasticity burnishing can also be used to induce compresses stress in fillets and cold work mandrels can be used for holes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Increases in fatigue life and strength are proportionally related to the depth of the compressive residual stresses imparted.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Shot peening imparts compressive residual stresses approximately 0.005 inches (0.1 mm) deep, while laser peening can go 0.040 to 0.100 inches (1 to 2.5 mm) deep, or deeper.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The use of deep cryogenic treatment has been shown to increase resistance to fatigue failure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Springs used in industry, auto racing and firearms have been shown to last up to six times longer when treated.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Heat checking, which is a form of thermal cyclic fatigue has been greatly delayed.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Changing the shape of a stress concentration such as a hole or cutout may be used to extend the life of a component.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Shape optimisation using numerical optimisation algorithms have been used to lower the stress concentration in wings and increase their life.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Composite materials can offer excellent resistance to fatigue loading.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In general, composites exhibit good fracture toughness and, unlike metals, increase fracture toughness with increasing strength.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The critical damage size in composites is also greater than that for metals.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The primary mode of damage in a metal structure is cracking.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] For metal, cracks propagate in a relatively well-defined manner with respect to the applied stress, and the critical crack size and rate of crack propagation can be related to specimen data through analytical fracture mechanics.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] However, with composite structures, there is no single damage mode which dominates.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Matrix cracking, delamination, debonding, voids, fiber fracture, and composite cracking can all occur separately and in combination, and the predominance of one or more is highly dependent on the laminate orientations and loading conditions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In addition, the unique joints and attachments used for composite structures often introduce modes of failure different from those typified by the laminate itself.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The composite damage propagates in a less regular manner and damage modes can change.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Experience with composites indicates that the rate of damage propagation in does not exhibit the two distinct regions of initiation and propagation like metals.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The crack initiation range in metals is propagation, and there is a significant quantitative difference in rate while the difference appears to be less apparent with composites.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Fatigue cracks of composites may form in the matrix and propagate slowly since the matrix carries such a small fraction of the applied stress.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] And the fibers in the wake of the crack experience fatigue damage.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In many cases, the damage rate is accelerated by deleterious interactions with the environment like oxidation or corrosion of fibers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Following King Louis-Philippe I's celebrations at the Palace of Versailles, a train returning to Paris crashed in May 1842 at Meudon after the leading locomotive broke an axle.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The carriages behind piled into the wrecked engines and caught fire.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] At least 55 passengers were killed trapped in the locked carriages, including the explorer Jules Dumont d'Urville.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This accident is known in France as the *"Catastrophe ferroviaire de Meudon"*.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The accident was witnessed by the British locomotive engineer Joseph Locke and widely reported in Britain.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] It was discussed extensively by engineers, who sought an explanation.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The derailment had been the result of a broken locomotive axle.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Rankine's investigation of broken axles in Britain highlighted the importance of stress concentration, and the mechanism of crack growth with repeated loading.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] His and other papers suggesting a crack growth mechanism through repeated stressing, however, were ignored, and fatigue failures occurred at an ever-increasing rate on the expanding railway system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Other spurious theories seemed to be more acceptable, such as the idea that the metal had somehow "crystallized".
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The notion was based on the crystalline appearance of the fast fracture region of the crack's surface, but ignored the fact that the metal was already highly crystalline.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Two de Havilland Comet passenger jets broke up in mid-air and crashed within a few months of each other in 1954.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] As a result, systematic tests were conducted on a fuselage immersed and pressurised in a water tank.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] After the equivalent of 3,000 flights, investigators at the Royal Aircraft Establishment (RAE) were able to conclude that the crash had been due to failure of the pressure cabin at the forward Automatic Direction Finder window in the roof.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This 'window' was in fact one of two apertures for the aerials of an electronic navigation system in which opaque fibreglass panels took the place of the window 'glass'.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The failure was a result of metal fatigue caused by the repeated pressurisation and de-pressurisation of the aircraft cabin.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Also, the supports around the windows were riveted, not bonded, as the original specifications for the aircraft had called for.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The problem was exacerbated by the punch rivet construction technique employed.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Unlike drill riveting, the imperfect nature of the hole created by punch riveting caused manufacturing defect cracks which may have caused the start of fatigue cracks around the rivet.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In addition, it was discovered that the stresses around pressure cabin apertures were considerably higher than had been anticipated, especially around sharp-cornered cut-outs, such as windows.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] As a result, all future jet airliners would feature windows with rounded corners, greatly reducing the stress concentration.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This was a noticeable distinguishing feature of all later models of the Comet.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Investigators from the RAE told a public inquiry that the sharp corners near the Comets' window openings acted as initiation sites for cracks.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The skin of the aircraft was also too thin, and cracks from manufacturing stresses were present at the corners.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] In March 1981, the investigative report concluded that the rig collapsed owing to a fatigue crack in one of its six bracings (bracing D-6), which connected the collapsed D-leg to the rest of the rig.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This was traced to a small 6 mm fillet weld which joined a non-load-bearing flange plate to this D-6 bracing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] This flange plate held a sonar device used during drilling operations.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] The poor profile of the fillet weld contributed to a reduction in its fatigue strength.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Further, the investigation found considerable amounts of lamellar tearing in the flange plate and cold cracks in the butt weld.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/fatigue-material] Cold cracks in the welds, increased stress concentrations due to the weakened flange plate, the poor weld profile, and cyclical stresses (which would be common in the North Sea), seemed to collectively play a role in the rig's collapse.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Classically this was done with a SIMO (single-input, multiple-output) approach, that is, one excitation point, and then the response is measured at many other points.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] In the past a hammer survey, using a fixed accelerometer and a roving hammer as excitation, gave a MISO (multiple-input, single-output) analysis, which is mathematically identical to SIMO, due to the principle of reciprocity.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] In recent years MIMO (multi-input, multiple-output) have become more practical, where partial coherence analysis identifies which part of the response comes from which excitation source.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Using multiple shakers leads to a uniform distribution of the energy over the entire structure and a better coherence in the measurement.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] A single shaker may not effectively excite all the modes of a structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Typical excitation signals can be classed as impulse, broadband, swept sine, chirp, and possibly others.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Each has its own advantages and disadvantages.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] The analysis of the signals typically relies on Fourier analysis.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] The resulting transfer function will show one or more resonances, whose characteristic mass, frequency and damping ratio can be estimated from the measurements.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] The animated display of the mode shape is very useful to NVH (noise, vibration, and harshness) engineers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] The results can also be used to correlate with finite element analysis normal mode solutions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] In structural engineering, modal analysis uses the overall mass and stiffness of a structure to find the various periods at which it will naturally resonate.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] These periods of vibration are very important to note in earthquake engineering, as it is imperative that a building's natural frequency does not match the frequency of expected earthquakes in the region in which the building is to be constructed.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] If a structure's natural frequency matches an earthquake's frequency, the structure may continue to resonate and experience structural damage.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Modal analysis is also important in structures such as bridges where the engineer should attempt to keep the natural frequencies away from the frequencies of people walking on the bridge.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] This may not be possible and for this reasons when groups of people are to walk along a bridge, for example a group of soldiers, the recommendation is that they break their step to avoid possibly significant excitation frequencies.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Other natural excitation frequencies may exist and may excite a bridge's natural modes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Other aerodynamic loading issues are dealt with by minimizing the area of the structure projected to the oncoming wind and to reduce wind generated oscillations of, for example, the hangers in suspension bridges.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Although modal analysis is usually carried out by computers, it is possible to hand-calculate the period of vibration of any high-rise building through idealization as a fixed-ended cantilever with lumped masses.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] The basic idea of a modal analysis in electrodynamics is the same as in mechanics.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] The application is to determine which electromagnetic wave modes can stand or propagate within conducting enclosures such as waveguides or resonators.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Once a set of modes has been calculated for a system, the response to any kind of excitation can be calculated as a superposition of modes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] This means that the response is the sum of the different mode shapes each one vibrating at its frequency.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] The weighting coefficients of this sum depend on the initial conditions and on the input signal.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] If the response is measured at point B in direction x (for example), for an excitation at point A in direction y, then the transfer function (crudely Bx/Ay in the frequency domain) is identical to that which is obtained when the response at Ay is measured when excited at Bx.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Again this assumes (and is a good test for) linearity.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] Identification methods are the mathematical backbone of modal analysis.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] They allow, through linear algebra, specifically through least square methods to fit large amounts of data to find the modal constants (modal mass, modal stiffness modal damping) of the system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/modal-analysis] The methods are divided on the basis of the kind of system they aim to study in SDOF (single degree of freedom) methods and MDOF (multiple degree of freedom systems) methods and on the basis of the domain in which the data fitting takes place in time domain methods and frequency domain methods.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Non-Destructive Testing (NDT/ NDT testing) Techniques or Methodologies allow the investigator to carry out examinations without invading the integrity of the engineering specimen under observation while providing an elaborate view of the surface and structural discontinuities and obstructions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The personnel carrying out these methodologies require specialized NDT Training as they involve handling delicate equipment and subjective interpretation of the NDT inspection/NDT testing results.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Visual inspection (VT), the most commonly applied NDT method, is quite often enhanced by the use of magnification, borescopes, cameras, or other optical arrangements for direct or remote viewing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The internal structure of a sample can be examined for a volumetric inspection with penetrating radiation (RT), such as X-rays, neutrons or gamma radiation.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Sound waves are utilized in the case of ultrasonic testing (UT), another volumetric NDT method – the mechanical signal (sound) being reflected by conditions in the test article and evaluated for amplitude and distance from the search unit (transducer).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Another commonly used NDT method used on ferrous materials involves the application of fine iron particles (either suspended in liquid or dry powder – fluorescent or colored) that are applied to a part while it is magnetized, either continually or residually.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The particles will be attracted to leakage fields of magnetism on or in the test object, and form indications (particle collection) on the object's surface, which are evaluated visually.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Contrast and probability of detection for a visual examination by the unaided eye is often enhanced by using liquids to penetrate the test article surface, allowing for visualization of flaws or other surface conditions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] This method (liquid penetrant testing) (PT) involves using dyes, fluorescent or colored (typically red), suspended in fluids and is used for non-magnetic materials, usually metals.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Analyzing and documenting a nondestructive failure mode can also be accomplished using a high-speed camera recording continuously (movie-loop) until the failure is detected.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Detecting the failure can be accomplished using a sound detector or stress gauge which produces a signal to trigger the high-speed camera.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] These high-speed cameras have advanced recording modes to capture some non-destructive failures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] After the failure the high-speed camera will stop recording.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The captured images can be played back in slow motion showing precisely what happened before, during and after the nondestructive event, image by image.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] NDT is used in a variety of settings that covers a wide range of industrial activity, with new NDT methods and applications, being continuously developed.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Nondestructive testing methods are routinely applied in industries where a failure of a component would cause significant hazard or economic loss, such as in transportation, pressure vessels, building structures, piping, and hoisting equipment.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] In manufacturing, welds are commonly used to join two or more metal parts.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Because these connections may encounter loads and fatigue during product lifetime, there is a chance that they may fail if not created to proper specification.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] For example, the base metal must reach a certain temperature during the welding process, must cool at a specific rate, and must be welded with compatible materials or the joint may not be strong enough to hold the parts together, or cracks may form in the weld causing it to fail.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The typical welding defects (lack of fusion of the weld to the base metal, cracks or porosity inside the weld, and variations in weld density) could cause a structure to break or a pipeline to rupture.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Welds may be tested using NDT techniques such as industrial radiography or industrial CT scanning using X-rays or gamma rays, ultrasonic testing, liquid penetrant testing, magnetic particle inspection or via eddy current.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] In a proper weld, these tests would indicate a lack of cracks in the radiograph, show clear passage of sound through the weld and back, or indicate a clear surface without penetrant captured in cracks.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Welding techniques may also be actively monitored with acoustic emission techniques before production to design the best set of parameters to use to properly join two materials.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] In the case of high stress or safety critical welds, weld monitoring will be employed to confirm the specified welding parameters (arc current, arc voltage, travel speed, heat input etc.) are being adhered to those stated in the welding procedure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] This verifies the weld as correct to procedure prior to nondestructive evaluation and metallurgy tests.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Structure can be complex systems that undergo different loads during their lifetime, e.g.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Some complex structures, such as the turbo machinery in a liquid-fuel rocket, can also cost millions of dollars.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Engineers will commonly model these structures as coupled second-order systems, approximating dynamic structure components with springs, masses, and dampers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The resulting sets of differential equations are then used to derives a transfer function that models the behavior of the system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] In NDT, the structure undergoes a dynamic input, such as the tap of a hammer or a controlled impulse.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Key properties, such as displacement or acceleration at different points of the structure, are measured as the corresponding output.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] This output is recorded and compared to the corresponding output given by the transfer function and the known input.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Differences may indicate an inappropriate model (which may alert engineers to unpredicted instabilities or performance outside of tolerances), failed components, or an inadequate control system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Reference standards, which are structures that intentionally flawed in order to be compared with components intended for use in the field, are often used in NDT.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Reference standards can be with many NDT techniques, such as UT, RT and VT.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Several NDT methods are related to Clinical Procedures, such as radiography, ultrasonic testing, and visual testing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Technological improvements or upgrades in these NDT methods have migrated over from medical equipment advances, including digital radiography (DR), phased array ultrasonic testing (PAUT), and endoscopy (borescope or assisted visual inspection).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] This ISO 9712 requirements for principles for the qualification and certification of personnel who perform industrial non-destructive testing(NDT).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] NDT is divided into various *methods* of nondestructive testing, each based on a particular scientific principle.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] These methods may be further subdivided into various *techniques*.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The various methods and techniques, due to their particular natures, may lend themselves especially well to certain applications and be of little or no value at all in other applications.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Therefore, choosing the right method and technique is an important part of the performance of NDT.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Successful and consistent application of nondestructive testing techniques depends heavily on personnel training, experience and integrity.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Personnel involved in application of industrial NDT methods and interpretation of results should be certified, and in some industrial sectors certification is enforced by law or by the applied codes and standards.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] NDT professionals and managers can join NDTMA, a member organization of NDT Managers and Executives who work to provide a forum for the open exchange of managerial, technical and regulatory information.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Their annual conference is at the Golden Nugget in Las Vegas.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] **Personal Central Certification**: The concept of central certification is that an NDT operator can obtain certification from a central certification authority, that is recognized by most employers, third parties and/or government authorities.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Industrial standards for central certification schemes include ISO 9712, and ANSI/ASNT CP-106 (used for the ASNT ACCP scheme).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Certification under these standards involves training, work experience under supervision and passing a written and practical examination set up by the independent certification authority.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] EN 473 was another central certification scheme, very similar to ISO 9712, which was withdrawn when CEN replaced it with *EN ISO 9712* in 2012.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] In the United States employer based schemes are the norm, however central certification schemes exist as well.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The most notable is *ASNT Level III* (established in 1976–1977), which is organized by the American Society for Nondestructive Testing for Level 3 NDT personnel.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] *NAVSEA 250-1500 Archived 2021-01-21 at the Wayback Machine* is another US central certification scheme, specifically developed for use in the naval nuclear program.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Central certification is more widely used in the European Union, where certifications are issued by accredited bodies (independent organizations conforming to ISO 17024 and accredited by a national accreditation authority like UKAS).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The Pressure Equipment Directive (97/23/EC) actually enforces central personnel certification for the initial testing of steam boilers and some categories of pressure vessels and piping.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] European Standards harmonized with this directive specify personnel certification to EN 473.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Certifications issued by a national NDT society which is a member of the European Federation of NDT (EFNDT) are mutually acceptable by the other member societies under a multilateral recognition agreement.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Canada also implements an ISO 9712 central certification scheme, which is administered by Natural Resources Canada, a government department.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The aerospace sector worldwide sticks to employer based schemes.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] In America it is based mostly on the Aerospace Industries Association's (AIA) AIA-NAS-410 and in the European Union on the equivalent and very similar standard EN 4179.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] However EN 4179:2009 includes an option for central qualification and certification by a *National aerospace NDT board* or *NANDTB* (paragraph 4.5.2).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Most NDT personnel certification schemes listed above specify three "levels" of qualification and/or certification, usually designated as *Level 1*, *Level 2* and *Level 3* (although some codes specify Roman numerals, like *Level II*).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The standard US terminology for Nondestructive testing is defined in standard ASTM E-1316.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Some definitions may be different in European standard EN 1330.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] The response or evidence from an examination, such as a blip on the screen of an instrument.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] are those caused by factors not related to the principles of the testing method or by improper implementation of the method, like film damage in radiography, electrical interference in ultrasonic testing etc.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] are those caused by known features of the tested object, like gaps, threads, case hardening etc.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Determining if an indication is of a type to be investigated.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] For example, in electromagnetic testing, indications from metal loss are considered flaws because they should usually be investigated, but indications due to variations in the material properties may be harmless and nonrelevant.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] A type of discontinuity that must be investigated to see if it is rejectable.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] For example, porosity in a weld or metal loss.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] A flaw that is rejectable – i.e. does not meet acceptance criteria.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Defects are generally removed or repaired.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Probability of detection (POD) tests are a standard way to evaluate a nondestructive testing technique in a given set of circumstances, for example "What is the POD of lack of fusion flaws in pipe welds using manual ultrasonic testing?" The POD will usually increase with flaw size.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] A common error in POD tests is to assume that the percentage of flaws detected is the POD, whereas the percentage of flaws detected is merely the first step in the analysis.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Since the number of flaws tested is necessarily a limited number (non-infinite), statistical methods must be used to determine the POD for all possible defects, beyond the limited number tested.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Another common error in POD tests is to define the statistical sampling units (test items) as flaws, whereas a true sampling unit is an item that may or may not contain a flaw.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/non-destructive-testing] Guidelines for correct application of statistical methods to POD tests can be found in ASTM E2862 Standard Practice for Probability of Detection Analysis for Hit/Miss Data and MIL-HDBK-1823A Nondestructive Evaluation System Reliability Assessment, from the U.S.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] A **strain gauge** (also spelled **strain gage**) is a device used to measure strain on an object.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Ruge in 1938, the most common type of strain gauge consists of an insulating flexible backing which supports a metallic foil pattern.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The gauge is attached to the object by a suitable adhesive, such as cyanoacrylate.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Proper adhesion is critical, as any air gaps or flexibility in the bonding layer will introduce measurement errors known as creep or hysteresis.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] As the object is deformed, the foil is deformed, causing its electrical resistance to change.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] This resistance change, usually measured using a Wheatstone bridge, is related to the strain by the quantity known as the gauge factor.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Ruge independently invented the strain gauge.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Simmons was involved in a research project by Dätwyler and Clark at Caltech between 1936 and 1938.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] They researched the stress-strain behavior of metals under shock loads.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Simmons came up with an original way to measure the force introduced into the sample by equipping a dynamometer with fine resistance wires.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Ruge, a professor at MIT, on the other hand, conducted research in seismology.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] He tried to analyze the behavior of a model water tank installed on a vibration table.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] He was not able to utilize the standard optical strain measurement methods of his time due to the small scale and low strains in his model.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Hanns Meier) had the epiphany of measuring the resistance change caused by strain in metallic wires cemented on the thin walls of the water tank model.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The development of the strain gauge was essentially just a byproduct of other research projects.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Ruge developed a widely used and useful measurement tool due to the lack of an alternative at their times.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Ruge realized the commercial utility of the strain gauge.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] His employer at MIT waived all claims on the right of the invention, as they did not predict the economic and large-scale usage potential.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The strain gauge applications were quickly gaining traction as they served to indirectly detect all other quantities that induce strain.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Additionally, they were simple to install by the scientists, did not cause any obstruction or property changes to the observed object and thus falsifying the measurement results.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Probably the last and most important property was the ease of transmission of the electrical output signal.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] A strain gauge takes advantage of the physical property of electrical conductance and its dependence on the conductor's geometry.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] When an electrical conductor is stretched within the limits of its elasticity such that it does not break or permanently deform, it will become narrower and longer, which increases its electrical resistance end-to-end.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Conversely, when a conductor is compressed such that it does not buckle, it will broaden and shorten, which decreases its electrical resistance end-to-end.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] From the measured electrical resistance of the strain gauge, the amount of induced stress may be inferred.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] A typical strain gauge arranges a long, thin conductive strip in a zig-zag pattern of parallel lines.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] This does not increase the sensitivity, since the percentage change in resistance for a given strain for the entire zig-zag is the same as for any single trace.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] A single linear trace would have to be extremely thin, hence liable to overheating (which would change its resistance and cause it to expand), or would need to be operated at a much lower voltage, making it difficult to measure resistance changes accurately.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] For common metallic foil gauges, the gauge factor is usually a little over 2.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Foil gauges typically have active areas of about 2–10 mm2 in size.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] With careful installation, the correct gauge, and the correct adhesive, strains up to at least 10% can be measured.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] An excitation voltage is applied to input leads of the gauge network, and a voltage reading is taken from the output leads.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Typical input voltages are 5 V or 12 V and typical output readings are in millivolts.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Foil strain gauges are used in many situations.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Different applications place different requirements on the gauge.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] In most cases the orientation of the strain gauge is significant.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Strain gauges are attached to the substrate with a special glue.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The type of glue depends on the required lifetime of the measurement system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] For short term measurements (up to some weeks) cyanoacrylate glue is appropriate, for long lasting installation epoxy glue is required.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Usually epoxy glue requires high temperature curing (at about 80-100 °C).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The preparation of the surface where the strain gauge is to be glued is of the utmost importance.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The surface must be smoothed (e.g. with very fine sand paper), deoiled with solvents, the solvent traces must then be removed and the strain gauge must be glued immediately after this to avoid oxidation or pollution of the prepared area.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] If these steps are not followed the strain gauge binding to the surface may be unreliable and unpredictable measurement errors may be generated.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Strain gauge based technology is used commonly in the manufacture of pressure sensors.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The gauges used in pressure sensors themselves are commonly made from silicon, polysilicon, metal film, thick film, and bonded foil.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Variations in temperature will cause a multitude of effects.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The object will change in size by thermal expansion, which will be detected as a strain by the gauge.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Resistance of the gauge will change, and resistance of the connecting wires will change.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Most strain gauges are made from a constantan alloy.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Various constantan alloys and Karma alloys have been designed so that the temperature effects on the resistance of the strain gauge itself largely cancel out the resistance change of the gauge due to the thermal expansion of the object under test.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Because different materials have different amounts of thermal expansion, self-temperature compensation (STC) requires selecting a particular alloy matched to the material of the object under test.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Strain gauges that are not self-temperature-compensated (such as isoelastic alloy) can be temperature compensated by use of the dummy gauge technique.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] A dummy gauge (identical to the active strain gauge) is installed on an unstrained sample of the same material as the test specimen.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The sample with the dummy gauge is placed in thermal contact with the test specimen, adjacent to the active gauge.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The dummy gauge is wired into a Wheatstone bridge on an adjacent arm to the active gauge so that the temperature effects on the active and dummy gauges cancel each other.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Every material reacts when it heats up or when it cools down.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] This will cause strain gauges to register a deformation in the material which will make it change signal.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] To prevent this from happening strain gauges are made so they will compensate this change due to temperature.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Dependent on the material of the surface where the strain gauge is assembled on, a different expansion can be measured.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Temperature effects on the lead wires can be cancelled by using a "3-wire bridge" or a "4-wire ohm circuit" (also called a "4-wire Kelvin connection").
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] In any case it is a good engineering practice to keep the Wheatstone bridge voltage drive low enough to avoid the self heating of the strain gauge.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The self heating of the strain gauge depends on its mechanical characteristic (large strain gauges are less prone to self heating).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Low voltage drive levels of the bridge reduce the sensitivity of the overall system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Structural health monitoring (SHM) is used to monitor structures after their completion.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] To prevent failures, strain gauges are used to detect and locate damages and creep.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] A specific example is the monitoring of bridge cables increasing safety by detecting possible damages.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Also, the bridge's behavior to unusual loads such as special heavy-duty transports can be analyzed.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Measuring the strain of skin can provide a multitude of biomechanic measurements such as posture, joint rotation, respiration and swelling both in humans and other animals.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Resistive foil strain gauges are seldom used for these applications, however, due to their low strain limit.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Instead, soft and deformable strain gauges are often attached to a host garment, to make it simple to apply the sensor to the correct part of the body, though sometimes they are attached directly to the skin.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Typically in these applications, such soft strain gauges are known as stretch sensors.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] For medical use, the sensors must be accurate and repeatable which typically requires the use of capacitive stretch sensors.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Many objects and materials in industrial applications have a finite life.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] To improve their lifetime and cost of ownership, predictive maintenance principles are used.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Strain gauges can be used to monitor the strain as an indicator of fatigue in materials to enable software systems to predict when certain components need to be replaced or serviced.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Resistive foil gauges can be used to instrument stiff materials like metals, ceramics, composites and similar, whereas highly elastic strain gauges are used to monitor softer materials such as rubber, plastics, textiles and the like.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] In aviation, strain gauges are the standard approach to measuring the structural load and calculating wing deflection.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Strain gauges are fixed in several locations on the aircraft.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] However, deflection measurement systems have been shown to measure strains reliably remotely.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] This reduces instrumentation weight on the aircraft and thus is replacing (certain) strain gauges.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] There are also applications where it isn't first obvious that you would measure strain to get to the wanted result.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] So for example in the detection of intruders on certain structures, strain gauges can be used to detect the presence of such an intruder.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] This is done by measuring the slight change in strain of the said structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] In some applications, strain gauges add mass and damping to the vibration profiles of the hardware they are intended to measure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] In the turbomachinery industry, one used alternative to strain gauge technology in the measurement of vibrations on rotating hardware is the non-intrusive stress measurement system, which allows measurement of blade vibrations without any blade or disc-mounted hardware.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Strain Gauge measurement devices are prone to drift problems.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Additionally, their manufacturing requires precise requirements during all the production steps.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] So there are multiple different ways of also measuring strain.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Strain can also be measured using digital image correlation (DIC).
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] With this technique one or two cameras are used in conjunction with a DIC software to track features on the surface of components to detect small motion.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The full strain map of the tested sample can be calculated, providing similar display as a finite-element analysis.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] This technique is used in many industries to replace traditional strain gauges or other sensors like extensometers, string pots, LVDT, accelerometers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The accuracy of commercially available DIC software typically ranges around 1/100 to 1/30 of a pixel for displacement measurements which result in strain sensitivity between 20 and 100 parts per million.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The DIC technique allows to quickly measure shape, displacements and strain non-contact, avoiding some issues of traditional contacting methods, especially with impacts, high-strain, high-temperature or high-cycle fatigue testing.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Stefan Keil published the first edition of a detailed book about strain gauges and how to use them called *Dehnungsmessstreifen*.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Although this first edition was only published in German, it became popular outside of Germany because of the wide range of uses of strain gauges in different fields.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] After more than 20 years (in 2017), he published a second edition that was translated into English, hence available to more engineers that use strain gauges.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] This newest book is titled *Technology and Practical Use of Strain Gages*.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The term *strain gauge* can be encountered in sociology.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The social strain gauge theory is an approach to understanding accusations of witchcraft and sorcery.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] South African anthropologist Maxwell Marwick studied these sociological phenomena in Zambia and Malawi in 1965.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] Accusations of witchcraft reflect strain on relationships or a whole social structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/strain-gauge] The theory says that the sorcery accusations were a pressure valve of society.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] In an operational environment, structures degrade with age and use.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Long term SHM outputs periodically updated information regarding the ability of the structure to continue performing its intended function.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] After extreme events, such as earthquakes or blast loading, SHM is used for rapid condition screening.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] SHM is intended to provide reliable information regarding the integrity of the structure in near real time.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The SHM process involves selecting the excitation methods, the sensor types, number and locations, and the data acquisition/storage/transmittal hardware commonly called health and usage monitoring systems.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Measurements may be taken to either directly detect any degradation or damage that may occur to a system or indirectly by measuring the size and frequency of loads experienced to allow the state of the system to be predicted.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] To directly monitor the state of a system it is necessary to identify features in the acquired data that allows one to distinguish between the undamaged and damaged structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] One of the most common feature extraction methods is based on correlating measured system response quantities, such a vibration amplitude or frequency, with observations of the degraded system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Damage accumulation testing, during which significant structural components of the system under study are degraded by subjecting them to realistic loading conditions, can also be used to identify appropriate features.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] This process may involve induced-damage testing, fatigue testing, corrosion growth, or temperature cycling to accumulate certain types of damage in an accelerated fashion.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Qualitative and non-continuous methods have long been used to evaluate structures for their capacity to serve their intended purpose.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Since the beginning of the 19th century, railroad wheel-tappers have used the sound of a hammer striking the train wheel to evaluate if damage was present.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] In rotating machinery, vibration monitoring has been used for decades as a performance evaluation technique.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Two techniques in the field of SHM are wave propagation based techniques and vibration based techniques.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] An example of this technology is embedding sensors in structures like bridges and aircraft.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] These sensors provide real time monitoring of various structural changes like stress and strain.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] In the case of civil engineering structures, the data provided by the sensors is usually transmitted to a remote data acquisition centres.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Commonly known as Structural Health Assessment (SHA) or SHM, this concept is widely applied to various forms of infrastructures, especially as countries all over the world enter into an even greater period of construction of various infrastructures ranging from bridges to skyscrapers.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] It is necessary to employ signal processing and statistical classification to convert sensor data on the infrastructural health status into damage info for assessment.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] i) What are the life-safety and/or economic justification for performing the SHM?
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] ii) How is damage defined for the system being investigated and, for multiple damage possibilities, which cases are of the most concern?
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] iii) What are the conditions, both operational and environmental, under which the system to be monitored functions?
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] iv) What are the limitations on acquiring data in the operational environment?
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Operational evaluation begins to set the limitations on what will be monitored and how the monitoring will be accomplished.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] This evaluation starts to tailor the damage identification process to features that are unique to the system being monitored and tries to take advantage of unique features of the damage that is to be detected.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The data acquisition portion of the SHM process involves selecting the excitation methods, the sensor types, number and locations, and the data acquisition/storage/transmittal hardware.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Again, this process will be application specific.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Economic considerations will play a major role in making these decisions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The intervals at which data should be collected is another consideration that must be addressed.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Because data can be measured under varying conditions, the ability to normalize the data becomes very important to the damage identification process.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] As it applies to SHM, data normalization is the process of separating changes in sensor reading caused by damage from those caused by varying operational and environmental conditions.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] One of the most common procedures is to normalize the measured responses by the measured inputs.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] When environmental or operational variability is an issue, the need can arise to normalize the data in some temporal fashion to facilitate the comparison of data measured at similar times of an environmental or operational cycle.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Sources of variability in the data acquisition process and with the system being monitored need to be identified and minimized to the extent possible.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] In general, not all sources of variability can be eliminated.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Therefore, it is necessary to make the appropriate measurements such that these sources can be statistically quantified.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Variability can arise from changing environmental and test conditions, changes in the data reduction process, and unit-to-unit inconsistencies.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Data cleansing is the process of selectively choosing data to pass on to or reject from the feature selection process.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The data cleansing process is usually based on knowledge gained by individuals directly involved with the data acquisition.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] As an example, an inspection of the test setup may reveal that a sensor was loosely mounted and, hence, based on the judgment of the individuals performing the measurement, this set of data or the data from that particular sensor may be selectively deleted from the feature selection process.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Signal processing techniques such as filtering and re-sampling can also be thought of as data cleansing procedures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Finally, the data acquisition, normalization, and cleansing portion of SHM process should not be static.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Insight gained from the feature selection process and the statistical model development process will provide information regarding changes that can improve the data acquisition process.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The area of the SHM process that receives the most attention in the technical literature is the identification of data features that allows one to distinguish between the undamaged and damaged structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Inherent in this feature selection process is the condensation of the data.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The best features for damage identification are, again, application specific.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] One of the most common feature extraction methods is based on correlating measured system response quantities, such a vibration amplitude or frequency, with the first-hand observations of the degrading system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Another method of developing features for damage identification is to apply engineered flaws, similar to ones expected in actual operating conditions, to systems and develop an initial understanding of the parameters that are sensitive to the expected damage.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The flawed system can also be used to validate that the diagnostic measurements are sensitive enough to distinguish between features identified from the undamaged and damaged system.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The use of analytical tools such as experimentally-validated finite element models can be a great asset in this process.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] In multiple cases the analytical tools are used to perform numerical experiments where the flaws are introduced through computer simulation.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Insight into the appropriate features can be gained from several types of analytical and experimental studies as described above and is usually the result of information obtained from some combination of these studies.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The operational implementation and diagnostic measurement technologies needed to perform SHM produce more data than traditional uses of structural dynamics information.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] A condensation of the data is advantageous and necessary when comparisons of multiple feature sets obtained over the lifetime of the structure are envisioned.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Also, because data will be acquired from a structure over an extended period of time and in an operational environment, robust data reduction techniques must be developed to retain feature sensitivity to the structural changes of interest in the presence of environmental and operational variability.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] To further aid in the extraction and recording of quality data needed to perform SHM, the statistical significance of the features should be characterized and used in the condensation process.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The portion of the SHM process that has received the least attention in the technical literature is the development of statistical models for discrimination between features from the undamaged and damaged structures.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Statistical model development is concerned with the implementation of the algorithms that operate on the extracted features to quantify the damage state of the structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The algorithms used in statistical model development usually fall into three categories.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] When data are available from both the undamaged and damaged structure, the statistical pattern recognition algorithms fall into the general classification category, commonly referred to as supervised learning.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Group classification and regression analysis are categories of supervised learning algorithms.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Unsupervised learning refers to algorithms that are applied to data not containing examples from the damaged structure.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Outlier or novelty detection is the primary class of algorithms applied in unsupervised learning applications.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] All of the algorithms analyze statistical distributions of the measured or derived features to enhance the damage identification process.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] Health monitoring of large bridges can be performed by simultaneous measurement of loads on the bridge and effects of these loads.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] The state of Oregon in the United States, Department of Transportation Bridge Engineering Department has developed and implemented a Structural Health Monitoring (SHM) program as referenced in this technical paper by Steven Lovejoy, Senior Engineer.
[src:structural-health-monitoring/structural-health-monitoring] References are available that provide an introduction to the application of fiber optic sensors to Structural Health Monitoring on bridges.
